{{ElectionsNY}}
The '''[[United States Senate]] election in [[New York]] in 2000''' was held on November 7, 2000.  [[First Lady of the United States]] [[Hillary Rodham Clinton]], the first First Lady to run for political office, defeated [[United States House of Representatives|Congressman]] [[Rick Lazio]].  The general election coincided with the [[2000 U.S. presidential election]].

The race began in November 1998 when four-term incumbent New York Senator [[Daniel Patrick Moynihan]] announced his retirement. Both the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] and [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] sought high-profile candidates to compete for the open seat. By early 1999 Clinton and [[Mayor of New York City]] [[Rudy Giuliani]] were the likely respective nominees. The lead in statewide polls swung from Clinton to Giuliani and back to Clinton as the campaigns featured successful strategies, mistakes, and dealing with current events. In late April and May 2000, Giuliani's medical, romantic, marital, and political lives all collided in a tumultuous four-week period, culminating in his withdrawing from the race.

The Republicans chose lesser-known Congressman [[Rick Lazio]] to replace him.  The election included a record $90 million in campaign expenditures between Clinton, Lazio, and Giuliani and national visibility.  Clinton showed strength in normally Republican upstate areas and a debate blunder by Lazio solidified Clinton's previously shaky support among women.  Clinton won the election in November 2000 with 55&nbsp;percent of the vote to Lazio's 43&nbsp;percent.

==An open seat draws high-profile candidates==
When four-term New York Senator [[Daniel Patrick Moynihan]] announced his retirement in November 1998,<ref name="cnn110698">{{cite news | url=http://www.cnn.com/ALLPOLITICS/stories/1998/11/06/moynihan/ | title=Moynihan tells friends he won't seek another term | author=[[John King (journalist)|John King]] | publisher=[[CNN]] | date=1998-11-06 | accessdate=2007-11-01}}</ref> his previously safe Senate seat became open in the [[U.S. Senate election, 2000|2000 U.S. Senate election]].  Both parties tried to find high-profile candidates to run for it.

[[Mayor of New York City|New York City Mayor]] [[Rudy Giuliani]], who was prevented by term limits from running for mayoral reelection in 2001, immediately indicated interest.<ref name="cnn110698"/> Due to his high profile and visibility, Giuliani was supported by the state Republican Party, even though he had irritated many by endorsing incumbent Democratic Governor [[Mario Cuomo]] over Republican [[George Pataki]] in 1994.<ref>{{cite web|title=1994 Ad|url=http://www.findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m1282/is_n22_v46/ai_15999869|publisher=[[National Review]]|date=1994-11-21|accessdate=2007-11-02}}</ref>  
Giuliani became the presumptive Republican nominee, and by April 1999 had formed a formal exploratory committee for a Senate run.  There were still possible Republican primary opponents. [[Rick Lazio]], a [[United States House of Representatives|Congressman]] representing [[Suffolk County, New York|Suffolk County]] on [[Long Island]], was raising money and had a candidacy announcement scheduled for August 16;<ref name="cnn081199">{{cite news | url=http://www.cnn.com/ALLPOLITICS/stories/1999/08/11/senate.2000/lazio.suspends/index.html | title=Lazio suspends Senate plans | publisher=[[CNN.com]] | date=1999-08-11 | accessdate=2007-11-02}}</ref> he had openly discussed a primary against Giuliani, believing his more conservative record would be appealing to Republican primary voters.  In early August, under pressure from state and national Republican figures, Pataki endorsed Giuliani.<ref name="cnn081199"/>  Pataki prevailed upon Lazio to forgo his candidacy, which Lazio agreed to despite frustration that Giuliani had still not officially announced that he was running; Lazio said, "If the mayor wants to be a candidate, I think he needs to get into this race. It's time to put the soap opera aside and step up to the plate."<ref name="cnn081199"/>  [[Nassau County, New York|Nassau County]] Congressman [[Peter T. King|Pete King]] also considered running and had raised some funds.<ref name="cnn081199"/>

[[Image:Giuliani1999CityAddress.jpg|thumb|200px|left|By the time of Mayor Giuliani's January 1999 State of the City address, he was already intending to run for the Senate in 2000.]]
New York Congresswoman [[Nita Lowey]] was the candidate first expected to be the Democratic nominee,<ref name="wapo030299">{{cite news | url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/politics/campaigns/keyraces2000/stories/lowey030299.htm | title=Rep. Nita Lowey's Senate Bid on Standby | author=Kevin Merida | publisher=[[The Washington Post]] | date=1999-03-02 | accessdate=2007-11-01}}</ref> while other mentioned possible candidates included [[Secretary of Housing and Urban Development]] [[Andrew Cuomo]], [[New York State Comptroller]] [[Carl McCall]], and New York Congresswoman [[Carolyn Maloney]].<ref name="nydn123198">{{cite news | url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/news/1998/12/31/1998-12-31_cuomo_pushed_for_senate.html | title=Cuomo Pushed for Senate | author=Tracey Tully | publisher=[[New York Daily News]] | date=1998-12-31 | accessdate=2007-11-02}}</ref> State Democratic figures were concerned that neither Lowey nor the others had the star power to rival Giuliani, and that the seat would be lost.
Late in 1998,
prominent Democratic politicians and advisors, including New York Representative [[Charles Rangel]],<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.house.gov/apps/list/hearing/ny15_rangel/opedclintonharlem.html | title=Clinton Is Welcome in Harlem | author=[[Charles Rangel]] | publisher=[[U.S. House of Representatives]] | date=2001-02-14 | accessdate=2007-11-02}}</ref> urged First Lady [[Hillary Rodham Clinton]] to run for the New York Senate seat. An unprecedented action if she did it, Clinton spent considerable time mulling over the idea while Lowey waited in the wings.<ref name="wapo030299"/> Her political advisors told her the race would be difficult and some of them told her she would lose.<ref name="gerth-vannatta-book"/>  She waited for the [[impeachment of Bill Clinton|impeachment proceedings of Bill Clinton]] to conclude,<ref name="gerth-vannatta-book">{{cite book |last=Gerth |first=Jeff |authorlink=Jeff Gerth |coauthors=[[Don Van Natta, Jr.]] |title=Her Way: The Hopes and Ambitions of Hillary Rodham Clinton |year=2007 |publisher=[[Little, Brown and Company]] |location=New York |isbn=0-316-01742-6 }}, pp. 203-204.</ref> which it did with his acquittal on February 12, 1999.

== The early Clinton campaign==
On February 16, 1999, the First Lady's office announced that she was considering running for the Senate position.<ref name="gerth-vannatta-book"/>  Once it was clear Clinton was going to run, Lowey stepped aside, although she would be disappointed at the lost opportunity.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://marcambinder.theatlantic.com/archives/2008/11/clinton_move_starts_more_senat.php | title=Clinton move starts more Senate jockeying | author=[[Marc Ambinder|Ambinder, Marc]] | publisher=''[[The Atlantic]]'' | date=2008-11-21 | accessdate=2008-12-01}}</ref>  On July 7, 1999, Clinton formally announced an exploratory committee for the Senate run;<ref name="gvn-208">Gerth, Van Natta Jr., ''Her Way'', pp. 208-209.</ref> the setting was Moynihan's farm in [[Pindars Corners, New York|Pindars Corners]], in rural [[Delaware County, New York|Delaware County]].<ref name="bernstein-book">{{cite book |last=Bernstein |first=Carl |authorlink=Carl Bernstein |coauthors= |title=A Woman in Charge: The Life of Hillary Rodham Clinton |year=2007 |publisher=[[Knopf]] |location=New York |isbn=0-3754-0766-9 }}, p. 540.</ref> Bill Clinton was less than enthusiastic about her candidacy.<ref name="gvn-208"/><ref name="bernstein-book"/> The staging of the event was brokered by the Clintons' political consultant [[Mandy Grunwald]].<ref name="nyt072099">{{cite news | url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9900E7DD1E3FF933A15754C0A96F958260 | title=Public Lives: A Top Adviser to a Much-Advised First Lady | author=[[Elisabeth Bumiller]] | publisher=[[The New York Times]] | date=1999-07-20 | accessdate=2007-10-24}}</ref>  Hillary Clinton embarked upon a "listening tour" of all parts of New York after her entrance into the race.<ref name="lh">[[Hillary Rodham Clinton]], ''[[Living History]]'', [[Simon & Schuster]], 2003, ISBN 0-7432-2224-5, pp. 508.</ref>  She planned to visit all 62 counties in the New York, talking to New Yorkers in small-group settings according to the principles of [[retail politics]].<ref name="gvn-210">Gerth, Van Natta Jr., ''Her Way'', p. 210.</ref> During the race, she spent considerable time campaigning in traditionally Republican upstate regions. Clinton faced charges of [[carpetbagging]],<ref name="salon112707"/> since she had never resided in the State of New York nor directly participated in state politics prior to her Senate race. 

Meanwhile, in September 1999, the Clintons purchased a $1.5 million home<ref name="salon112707"/> in [[Chappaqua, New York]], north of [[New York City]].<ref>{{cite news | author=[[Adam Nagourney]] | url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9503E5D8153AF930A3575AC0A96F958260 | title=With Some Help, Clintons Purchase a White House | publisher=''[[The New York Times]]'' | date=September 3, 1999 | accessdate=2007-06-02}}</ref>  Even the commonplace activity of [[house hunting]] leading up to this was the subject of considerable media attention;<ref name="nyt082999">{{cite news | author=[[Adam Nagourney]] | title= Unusual Scrutiny for a Senate Race: This Time It's Personal | url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9D00E4DE103BF93AA1575BC0A96F958260 | date=1999-08-29 | publisher=[[The New York Times]] | accessdate=2007-09-30}}</ref> coverage of personal lives would be the norm in this contest of two "electrifying and polarizing figures".<ref name="nyt082999"/>

The early stages of her campaign were not without mistakes,<ref name="lh-509"/> and as she later wrote, "Mistakes in New York politics aren't easily brushed aside."<ref name="lh-509">''Living History'', p. 509.</ref>
In a much-publicized move, Clinton donned a [[New York Yankees]] baseball cap at a June 1999 event when she had been a lifelong fan of the [[Chicago Cubs]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F07E1DD1738F932A25755C0A96F958260 | title= Mrs. Clinton May Steal Mayor's Yankee Fan Base | author=Katherine Q. Seelye | publisher=''[[The New York Times]]'' | date=1999-06-11 | accessdate=2008-02-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.time.com/time/pacific/magazine/20001120/first_lady.html | title=Capitol Hill | author=[[Margaret Carlson]] | publisher=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] | date=2000-11-20 | accessdate=2007-12-08}}</ref><ref name="bw102500">{{cite news | url=http://www.businessweek.com/bwdaily/dnflash/oct2000/nf20001025_071.htm | title=The Subway Series, Hillary, and Rick | author=Ciro Scotti | publisher=[[BusinessWeek]] | date=2000-10-25 | accessdate=2007-12-08}}</ref> This brought her much criticism,<ref name="bw102500"/><ref name="nym101600"/> and Thomas Kuiper would later write an anti-Clinton book titled: ''I've Always Been a Yankees Fan: Hillary Clinton in Her Own Words''.  Clinton said she had to develop an [[American League]] rooting interest, since fans of the Cubs were not expected to root for the American League [[Chicago White Sox]].<ref name="nym101600">{{cite news | url=http://nymag.com/nymetro/news/sports/features/3943/ | title=Baseball Ballot | author=Chris Smith & Jessica Lustig | publisher=[[New York (magazine)|New York magazine]] | date=2000-10-16 | accessdate=2007-12-08}}</ref>  In her 2003 autobiography, she said that putting on the hat had been a "bad move", but reiterated what had been reported in the press prior to the incident, that she had been "a die-hard [[Mickey Mantle]] fan;"<ref>''Living History'', p 509.</ref> the book included a photograph of her with a Yankees cap on from 1992.<ref>''Living History'', plate 40, first photo section.</ref>

[[Image:Hillaryandsuha.jpg|thumb|192px|right|[[Hillary Clinton]] kissing [[Suha Arafat]], a November 1999 political mistake that she recovered from.]]
More seriously, on November 11, 1999, at the dedication of a U.S.-funded health program in the [[West Bank]], she exchanged kisses with [[Suha Arafat]], wife of Palestinian President [[Yasser Arafat]], after Suha Arafat had delivered a speech claiming that [[Israel]] had deliberately poisoned Palestinians through environmental degradation and the use of "poisonous gas".<ref name="cnn-suha">{{cite news | url=http://www.cnn.com/WORLD/meast/9911/11/israel.hillary.02/ | title=Hillary Clinton decries 'inflammatory' Mideast rhetoric | publisher=[[CNN]] | date=1999-11-11 | accessdate=2007-12-08}}</ref>  Some Israeli supporters said that Clinton never should have kissed the wife of the Palestinian leader, especially after such inflammatory remarks. The following day, Clinton denounced Suha Arafat's allegations, and said that Palestinian negotiator [[Saeb Erekat]] had told her Suha Arafat had been referring to '[[tear gas]]' and not '[[poison gas]]'.<ref name="cnn-suha"/> The kiss became a campaign issue, especially with Jewish voters.<ref name="salon112707"/><ref>{{cite news | url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F00E3D9153DF937A25752C1A96F958260 | title= Hillary Clinton Strikes Back At Giuliani on Mideast Trip | author=Joel Greenberg | publisher=''[[The New York Times]]'' | date=1999-11-14 | accessdate=2008-02-20}}</ref><ref name="Shake"/>  Clinton said it as a formality akin to a handshake, saying that to not have done so would have caused a diplomatic incident.<ref name="Shake">{{cite news | url=http://archives.cnn.com/2000/ALLPOLITICS/stories/09/11/lazio.arafat.ap/ | title=Hillary Clinton's rival defends handshake with Arafat | author=Beth J. Harpaz | publisher=[[Associated Press]] for [[CNN]] | date=2000-09-11 | accessdate=2007-12-08}}</ref>  Clinton later wrote that the live [[Arabic language|Arabic]]-to-English translation had failed to convey the accurate nature of her remarks: "Had I been aware of her hateful words, I would have denounced them on the spot."<ref>''Living History'', pp. 509-510.</ref>

Somewhat surprisingly, Clinton faced an erosion of support from women voters during her campaign, with her numbers declining throughout 1999.<ref name="nyt022200">{{cite news | url=http://www.nytimes.com/2000/02/22/nyregion/clinton-campaign-confronts-erosion-of-women-s-support.html | title=Clinton Campaign Confronts Erosion of Women's Support | author=[[Elisabeth Bumiller]] | newspaper=[[The New York Times]] | date=2000-02-22 | accessdate=2010-02-21}}</ref>  This was partly a typical pattern seen with women candidates where they have an early surge of female support, which then wears off, and it was partly due to her early campaign stumbles.<ref name="nyt022200"/>  But it also reflected the particular set of mixed feelings that women had towards Clinton's marriage and the ambition and the power she derived from it.<ref name="nyt022200"/>  The problem was especially acute among some female demographics; one of her longtime advisers later said, "Women in the educated professional class? They fucking couldn't stand her. We could never figure out why. We had psychologists come in."<ref>{{cite book | first=Anne E. | last=Kornblut | authorlink=Anne E. Kornblut | title=Notes from the Cracked Ceiling: Hillary Clinton, Sarah Palin, and What It Will Take for a Woman to Win | publisher=[[Crown Books]] | location=New York | year=2009 | isbn=0-307-46425-3 | page=31}}</ref>  

Clinton's campaign to all counties, carried by a [[Ford Motor Company|Ford]] [[conversion van]],<ref name="gvn-210"/> helped to defuse the carpetbagger issue,<ref name="bernstein-542">Bernstein, ''A Woman in Charge'', p. 542</ref> with many New York residents saying that Clinton "seems like one of us."<ref name="gvn-210"/>  She discussed local issues such as [[price support]]s for the [[dairy industry]], fares for air travel, [[college tuition]] levels, and the [[brain drain]] in parts of the state.<ref name="salon112707">{{cite news | url=http://www.salon.com/news/feature/2007/11/27/rudy_hillary/ | title=When Rudy Met Hillary | author=Rob Polner | publisher=''[[Salon (magazine)|Salon]]'' | date=2007-11-27 | accessdate=2008-02-22}}</ref>  Her political positions were well matched to the different constituencies in the state that she targeted.<ref name="bernstein-542"/>  In a January 2000 appearance on the ''[[Late Show with David Letterman]]'', she established a rapport with the host that would continue throughout her Senate years and into her 2008 presidential campaign.<ref name="gvn-211">Gerth, Van Natta Jr., ''Her Way'', p. 211.</ref>  Clinton formally announced her official candidacy in [[Purchase, New York]] in February 2000,<ref name="gvn-211"/> adopting the simple name "Hillary" for her campaign literature.<ref name="gvn-211"/>

Distrustful of the press since [[Bill Clinton presidential campaign, 1992|her husband's 1992 presidential campaign]] and her early days as First Lady,<ref name="tnr111207">{{cite news | url=http://www.tnr.com/politics/story.html?id=6e01fdce-ad97-4dab-a07d-bf98dc52f681 | author=[[Michael Crowley]] | title=Bunker Hillary | publisher=[[The New Republic]] | date=2007-11-12 | accessdate=2007-12-06}}</ref> she imposed limits on her availability to the press van following her.  [[Associated Press]] reporter Beth Harpaz later recounted a typical day from this time: "But we'd been told there'd be no 'avail' today, and we'd accepted it. That didn't prevent me from feeling slightly humiliated. I was so worn down and so exasperated by the lack of access and the lack of news in this campaign that I'd given up fighting."<ref name="harpaz">{{cite book | last=Harpaz | first=Beth | title=The Girls in the Van: Covering Hillary | publisher=[[St. Martin's Press]] | year=2001 | isbn=0312302711}} p. 86.</ref>

==The early Giuliani campaign==
An early January 1999 [[Marist Institute of Public Opinion]] poll showed Giuliani trailing Clinton by 10 points.<ref name="nyt013100">{{cite news | url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9A05E3DB113CF932A05752C0A9669C8B63 | title=Losing the Women | author=Lee M. Miringoff | publisher=[[The New York Times]] | date=2000-01-31 | accessdate=2007-09-27}}</ref>  By January 2000, the Marist poll showed Giuliani up by 9 points.<ref name="nyt013100"/>  Giuliani's tactics involved intentionally baiting the Clinton campaign with deliberate overstatements, keeping them off balance and behind in the response cycle.<ref name="nyt112807">{{cite news | url=http://www.nytimes.com/2007/11/28/us/politics/28york.html | title=Senate Race That Fizzled Honed Skills for <U+2019>08 | author=[[Adam Nagourney]] | publisher=[[The New York Times]] | date=2007-11-28 | accessdate=2007-11-29}}</ref>  Giuliani emphasized his depiction of Clinton as a carpetbagger.  He made a one-day visit to [[Little Rock, Arkansas]], where he announced he would fly the Arkansas state flag over New York's City Hall.<ref name="nyt112807"/>  When Hillary Clinton visited New York from Washington, he said, <U+201C>I hope she knows the way. I hope she doesn<U+2019>t get lost on one of the side streets.<U+201D><ref name="nyt112807"/>  Giuliani's campaign prepared a 315-page [[opposition research]] dossier that went back to her time at [[Wellesley College]]; it included eleven pages of what they termed "Stupid Actions and Remarks".<ref name="nyt112807"/>  The Giuliani campaign had no problems raising money, getting over 40&nbsp;percent of its funds from out-of-state and outraising Clinton overall two-to-one.<ref name="salon112707"/>

The Giuliani campaign showed some structural weaknesses. So closely identified with New York City, he had somewhat limited appeal to naturally Republican voters in [[Upstate New York]].<ref name="nyt110699">{{cite news | url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9E06E0DD163AF935A35752C1A96F958260 | title= Looking for the Senator From All of New York | author=George Gates | publisher=[[The New York Times]] | date=1999-11-06 | accessdate=2007-09-27}}</ref>  The [[Farmersville Garbage Scandal]] was indicative of his lower levels of support upstate.<ref name="nyt110699"/><ref>{{cite web | url=http://concernedcitizens.homestead.com/newspagenew.html | title=What's a 'Community'? | publisher=Concerned Citizens of Cattaraugus County | date=2006-10-27 | accessdate=2007-12-08}}</ref>  By late December 1999, Clinton adapted to Giuliani's [[psychological warfare]], saying in response to one such gambit, "I can<U+2019>t be responding every time the mayor gets angry. Because that<U+2019>s all I would do."<ref name="nyt112807"/>  A February 2000 attempt by Giuliani to capitalize on a Clinton campaign event's accidental playing of [[Billy Joel]]'s suburban drug tale "[[Captain Jack (song)|Captain Jack]]"<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.vh1.com/artists/news/621078/02082000/joel_billy.jhtml | title=Billy Joel Did Start The Fire In NY Senate Campaign | author=Brian Hiatt | publisher=[[VH1]] | date=2000-02-08 | accessdate=2008-02-22}}</ref> led to more ridicule for him than for her.<ref name="salon112707"/>

On March 11, 2000, Giuliani and Clinton met face-to-face for the first time since the campaigning began, at the New York Inner Circle press dinner, an annual event in which New York politicians and the press corps stage skits, [[roast (comedy)|roast]] each other and make fun of themselves, with proceeds going to charity.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://1010wins.com/pages/8015.php?contentType=4&contentId=102423 | title=Our Staff: Glenn Schuck | publisher=[[WINS (AM)|WINS]] | accessdate=2007-12-08}}</ref>
Giuliani was on stage in male [[disco]] garb spoofing [[John Travolta]] in ''[[Saturday Night Fever]]'', but also appeared [[drag (clothing)|in drag]] in taped video clips that reworked the "Rudy/Rudia" theme of a past Inner Circle dinner,<ref>{{cite news | url=http://archive.salon.com/politics2000/feature/2000/03/13/trail_mix/index.html | title=Rudy does 'Saturday Night Fever' | author=Max Garrone | date=2000-03-13 | accessdate=2007-12-08}}</ref> as well as in an exchange with [[Joan Rivers]] that sought to make fun of Clinton.<ref name="ap0300">{{cite news | author=Beth J. Harpaz | url=http://www.hillary.org/hc/Hillary_Clinton_Forum_178_chat1.cgi | title=Spoofs Target First Lady, Giuliani | publisher=[[Associated Press]] | date=March 2000 | accessdate=2007-03-12}}</ref>  Other performers' skits made fun of Clinton's Yankees claim and the infidelity of her husband.<ref name="ap0300"/>

The [[New York Police Department]]'s fatal shooting of [[Patrick Dorismond]] on March 15, 2000 inflamed Giuliani's already strained relations with the city's minority communities,<ref name="gvn-211"/> and Clinton seized on it as a major campaign issue.<ref name="gvn-211"/>  By April, reports showed Clinton gaining upstate and generally outworking Giuliani, who stated that his duties as mayor prevented him from campaigning more.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=980DE4DB1E3FF93BA35757C0A9669C8B63 | title= Despite Polls, Giuliani Says That He Won't Alter His Campaign Style | author=[[Adam Nagourney]] | publisher=[[The New York Times]] | date=2000-04-08 | accessdate=2007-09-27}}</ref>  He gave priority to city duties over campaign activities.<ref name="nyt112807"/>  Some Giuliani aides and national Republican figures concluded that his interest in the campaign was flagging, as although he was desirous of winning in political combat against a Clinton, he was by nature an executive personality and the prospect of serving as one of a hundred legislators was unappealing to him.<ref name="nyt112807"/> 

By this time, Clinton was 8 to 10 points ahead of Giuliani in the polls.<ref name="gvn-211"/><ref>''Living History'', p. 515.</ref>  In retrospect, ''[[The New York Times]]'' would write that the battle so far between the two had comprised "a blistering year of mental gamesmanship, piercing attacks, contrasts in personalities and positions, and blunders, played out by two outsize political figures in a super-heated atmosphere."<ref name="nyt112807"/>

== A tumultuous four weeks ==
Giuliani's marriage to his wife, broadcast journalist and actress [[Donna Hanover]], had been distant since 1996, and the two were rarely seen in public together.<ref name="nyt050400">{{cite news | url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9E03E4D61E39F937A35756C0A9669C8B63 | title= Mayor Acknowledges 'Very Good Friend' | author=[[Elisabeth Bumiller]] | publisher=[[The New York Times]] | date=2000-05-04 | accessdate=2007-12-07}}</ref>  There had been no formal announcement of any change in their relationship, although Hanover had indicated that she and their children would not move to Washington if Giuliani won the race.<ref>{{cite news | title=New York Political Corner | publisher=[[New York Amsterdam News]] | date=2000-03-23}}</ref>  Beginning in October 1999, a new woman was being spotted at mayoral functions.<ref name="barrett">{{cite book | last=Barrett | first=Wayne | authorlink=Wayne Barrett | title=Rudy! An Investigative Biography of Rudolph Giuliani | publisher=[[Basic Books]] | year=2000 | isbn=0-7567-6114-X}} p. 434.</ref>  By March 2000, Giuliani had stopped wearing his wedding ring<ref name="nyt050400"/> and was being seen more in the company of this other woman, including at the Inner Circle press dinner, the [[St. Patrick's Day]] parade, and town hall meetings, but it was not yet fully clear whether the relationship was personal or professional.<ref name="harpaz-113">Harpaz, ''The Girls in the Van'', p. 113.</ref><ref name="nyt050700"/>  While this woman had become a frequent subject of insider talk among the New York political circle, she had not been mentioned in the press.<ref name=barrett/>

On April 20 Hanover announced that she would soon be taking over the lead role in [[Eve Ensler]]'s controversial play ''[[The Vagina Monologues]]''.<ref name="nyt042100">{{cite news |url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9807E7D61E31F932A15757C0A9669C8B63 | title= 'Monologues' Making A Political Connection | author=[[Jesse McKinley]] | publisher=[[The New York Times]] | date=2000-04-21 | accessdate=2007-12-07}}</ref>  Political observers speculated that Hanover was partly engaging in a political act against her husband, as Ensler was a friend and supporter of Hillary Clinton<ref name="nyt042100"/> and the role would not go over well with [[social conservative]]s within the Republican Party.  Giuliani declined to say whether he would attend one of her performances.<ref>{{cite news | title=People in the News | publisher=[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]] | date=2000-04-27}}</ref>  On April 22, the ''[[New York Post]]'' obtained photographs of Giuliani openly strolling on a Manhattan street with the other woman after they left a restaurant, but did not have more than a first name for her;<ref name="harpaz-113"/><ref name="barrett-437">Barrett, ''Rudy!'', p. 437.</ref> the ''Post'' sat on the story, but it was clear the relationship was a personal one.<ref name="harpaz-113"/>

On April 26, television channel [[NY1]] reported that Giuliani had undergone a second round of tests for [[prostate cancer]] at [[Mount Sinai Medical Center]];<ref name="nyt042700">{{cite news | url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9E05E5DD1E30F934A15757C0A9669C8B63 | title= Giuliani Is Tested For Prostate Cancer | publisher=[[The New York Times]] | date=2000-04-27 | accessdate=2007-12-07}}</ref> the same disease had led to the death of his father.<ref name="nyt042700"/>  On April 28, Giuliani held a news conference to announce that he did in fact have prostate cancer, but it was in an early stage.<ref name="nyt042800">{{cite news | url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9E0CE0D61F30F93BA15757C0A9669C8B63 | title=  Giuliani Fighting Prostate Cancer; Unsure on Senate | author=[[Elisabeth Bumiller]] | publisher=[[The New York Times]] | date=2000-04-28 | accessdate=2007-12-07}}</ref>  He was unsure of which of several types of treatment he might undergo, and that decision would impact whether he could stay in the senate race or not.<ref name="nyt042800"/>  Hanover was not present at the conference, but issued a note saying she would support him in his decision process.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9903E3DE1639F93BA15757C0A9669C8B63 | title=A Glimpse Of Giuliani, Man of Grace | author=[[Clyde Haberman]] | publisher=[[The New York Times]] | date=2000-04-28 | accessdate=2007-12-17}}</ref>

As Giuliani mulled over his medical options, on May 1 Hanover announced that she was postponing her appearance in ''The Vagina Monologues'' due to "personal family circumstances."<ref name="nyt050200">{{cite news | url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9407E4DA1339F931A35756C0A9669C8B63 | title= Giuliani's Wife Postpones Her Role in 'Monologues' | author=[[Elisabeth Bumiller]] | publisher=[[The New York Times]] | date=2000-05-02 | accessdate=2007-12-07}}</ref>  On May 2 the ''[[New York Daily News]]'' published a brief item about Giuliani's other woman, without name or description.<ref name="barrett-436">Barrett, ''Rudy!'', p. 436.</ref>  On May 3 the ''[[New York Post]]'' finally published its photographs of Giuliani and the woman, now identified as [[Judith Nathan]],<ref name="barrett-436"/> leaving a restaurant together,<ref name="nyt050400"/><ref name="nyt051100"/> under the front page headline "Rudy's Mystery Brunch Pal is Upper East Side Divorc<U+00E9>e".<ref>{{cite news | url=http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0005/06/rs.00.html | title=Joe Lockhart Discusses Bill Clinton's Press Coverage | work=[[Reliable Sources]] | publisher=[[CNN.com]] | date=2000-05-06 | accessdate=2007-12-17}}</ref>  (Some observers felt that Giuliani, known for his ability to manipulate the New York media,<ref name="nyt050800">{{cite news | publisher=[[The New York Times]] | date=May 8, 2000 | author=Joyce Purnick |url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9B01E4DF1338F93BA35756C0A9669C8B63|title='Good Friend,' A Marriage, And Voters|accessdate=2008-04-04}}</ref> had been eager for news of the relationship to come out.<ref name="barrett-437"/><ref name="nyt050800"/>)  Later that day, Giuliani responded to a barrage of questions on the subject at a news conference by acknowledging Judith Nathan publicly for the first time, calling her "a very good friend" and expressing his annoyance that her privacy was being invaded.<ref name="nyt050400"/>  The next days were filled with New York media coverage on Nathan's background and on the relationship.<ref name="barrett-437"/>  On May 6 Hanover held an unusually-located news conference at the back of [[St. Patrick's Cathedral, New York|St. Patrick's Cathedral]] before the funeral of [[Cardinal John O'Connor]];<ref name="nyt050700">{{cite news | url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9B06E3DE1238F934A35756C0A9669C8B63 | title= Hanover Says Her Marriage To Mayor Is 'Very Precious' | author=Katherine E. Finkelstein | publisher=[[The New York Times]] | date=2000-05-07 | accessdate=2007-12-08}}</ref> visibly trembling, she said, "I will be supportive of Rudy in his fight against his illness, as this marriage and this man have been very precious to me."<ref name="nyt050700"/>  The following day half the press tried to stake out Nathan's known locations while the rest pestered Nathan's hometown relatives in [[Hazleton, Pennsylvania]];<ref name="barrett-438">Barrett, ''Rudy!'', p. 438.</ref> Giuliani looked weak in a public appearance.<ref name="barrett-438"/>

On May 10, Giuliani held what ''The New York Times'' described as an "extraordinary, emotional news conference" in [[Bryant Park]] to announce that he was seeking a separation from Hanover,<ref name="nyt051100">{{cite news | url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9E04E7D8163BF932A25756C0A9669C8B63 | title=Giuliani and His Wife of 16 Years Are Separating | author=[[Elisabeth Bumiller]] | publisher=[[The New York Times]] | date=2000-05-11 | accessdate=2007-12-08}}</ref> saying, "This is very, very painful. For quite some time it's probably been apparent that Donna and I lead in many ways independent and separate lives."<ref name="nyt051100"/>  Regarding Nathan, Giuliani said "I'm going to need her now more than maybe I did before," making reference to his battle with cancer<ref name="nyt051100"/> and her background in nursing.<ref name="barrett"/> Regarding the senate race, he again did not commit to a decision, saying, "I don't really care about politics right now.  I'm thinking about my family, the people that I love and what can be done that's honest and truthful and that protects them the best.  I'm not thinking about politics. Politics comes at least second, maybe third, maybe fourth, somewhere else. It'll all work itself out some way politically."<ref name="nyt051100"/>  Giuliani had, however, neglected to inform Hanover in advance of his announcement; her reaction was described as distraught.<ref name="nyt051100"/>  Three hours later, she held her own news conference at [[Gracie Mansion]], where she said, "Today's turn of events brings me great sadness. I had hoped to keep this marriage together. For several years, it was difficult to participate in Rudy's public life because of his relationship with one staff member."<ref name="nyt051100"/>  In this, she was making reference to [[Cristyne Lategano]], the former communications director for Giuliani;<ref name="nyt051100"/><ref name="cbs051100"/> ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'' had reported in 1997 that Lategano and Giuliani were having an affair, which both of them had denied.<ref name="cbs051100">{{cite news | url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2000/05/11/politics/main194350.shtml | title=The Women In Giuliani's Life | publisher=[[CBS News]] | date=2000-05-11 | accessdate=2007-12-08}}</ref>  Hanover continued, "Beginning last May, I made a major effort to bring us back together. Rudy and I re-established some of our personal intimacy through the fall. At that point, he chose another path."<ref name="nyt051100"/>

State Republican leaders, who until now had avoided talk of replacements for Giuliani should he not run, now gave more attention to the matter, with the state party convention coming up on May 30.<ref name="nyt051100n">{{cite news | url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C04E5D9163BF932A25756C0A9669C8B63 | title=G.O.P. Politely Searches For an Alternative, Fast | author=[[Adam Nagourney]] | publisher=[[The New York Times]] | date=2000-05-11 | accessdate=2007-12-18}}</ref>  Former possible contenders [[Rick Lazio]] and [[Peter T. King|Pete King]] immediately indicated they were available;<ref name="nyt051100n"/><ref>{{cite news | url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9800EEDB103BF936A25756C0A9669C8B63 | title= Behind the Scenes, Efforts to Find a Possible Senate Replacement | author=Eric Lipton | publisher=[[The New York Times]] | date=2000-05-15 | accessdate=2007-12-18}}</ref> other names mentioned included Wall Street financier [[Theodore J. Forstmann]] and Governor Pataki, although the latter indicated no interest.<ref name="nyt051100n"/>
Giuliani continued to ponder his senate race decision; when he had dinner with Nathan on May 12, they were trailed by a flock of photographers.<ref name="nyt051400">{{cite news | url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9502EEDC133BF937A25756C0A9669C8B63 | title= Giuliani Drops Upstate Fund-Raising Trip | author=Sarah Kershaw | publisher=[[The New York Times]] | date=2000-05-14 | accessdate=2007-12-18}}</ref>  Giuliani canceled campaigning and fundraising trips to upstate New York and California on May 13, suggesting he would not run,<ref name="nyt051400"/> but then resumed fundraising and suggested he was inclined towards running on May 15.<ref name="nyt051600">{{cite news | url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9A0CE3DF1E3BF935A25756C0A9669C8B63 | title= Mayor Inclined Toward Run, But His Backers Are Nervous | author=[[Elisabeth Bumiller]] | publisher=[[The New York Times]] | date=2000-05-16 | accessdate=2007-12-18}}</ref>  Two Republican county chairmen became upset at the indecision, saying, "Like ''Waiting for Godot'', we have ''Waiting for Rudy''," and, "We need a decision. Like tomorrow would be nice. Because this is getting ridiculous."<ref name="nyt051600"/>  A top state Republican said, "He seem[s] to like the attention. He seems to be going through some sort of catharsis in public. And we're like psychiatrists watching it. I can't quite figure it out. I don't think anybody can."<ref name="nyt051600"/>  Clinton, meanwhile, said as little as possible about the situation, preferring to let Giuliani's drama play out on its own;<ref>{{cite news | url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9D04E6DB143BF931A25756C0A9669C8B63 | title=Mrs. Clinton Stays Quiet While Mayor Is in Spotlight | author=[[Adam Nagourney]] | publisher=[[The New York Times]] | date=2000-05-12 | accessdate=2007-12-18}}</ref> on May 17, as he huddled with his doctors over whether to choose surgery or radiation as his treatment<ref>{{cite news | url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9B05E2DA1F3BF934A25756C0A9669C8B63 | title= Pensively, Giuliani Still Debates His Future | author=[[Elisabeth Bumiller]] | publisher=[[The New York Times]] | date=2000-05-17 | accessdate=2007-12-18}}</ref> while facing conflicting political advice from his aides,<ref>{{cite news | url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9B05E2D9103BF936A25756C0A9669C8B63 | title= Conflicting Advice at City Hall Complicates Giuliani's Decision | author=[[Adam Nagourney]] | publisher=[[The New York Times]] | date=2000-05-15 | accessdate=2007-12-18}}</ref> she won the unanimous approval of delegates to the Democratic Party state convention at the [[Times Union Center|Pepsi Arena]] in [[Albany, New York]], giving a constrained acceptance speech because she did not know her general election opponent.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9B03EFD71F3BF934A25756C0A9669C8B63 | title= With Senate Rival Uncertain, Party Nominates Mrs. Clinton | author=[[Adam Nagourney]] | publisher=[[The New York Times]] | date=2000-05-17 | accessdate=2007-12-18}}</ref>

Finally, on May 19, Giuliani held what ''The New York Times'' again described as "an emotional, riveting news conference" that "reached a new level of introspection" to announce that he was dropping out of the senate race:<ref name="nyt052000">{{cite news | url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9B07E1DF103AF933A15756C0A9669C8B63 | title= The Mayor's Decision: The Overview: Cancer is Concern | author=[[Elisabeth Bumiller]] | publisher=[[The New York Times]] | date=2000-05-20 | accessdate=2007-12-18}}</ref>  "This is not the right time for me to run for office. If it were six months ago or it were a year from now or the timing were a little different, maybe it would be different. But it isn't different and that's the way life is."<ref name="nyt052000"/>  He added that, "I used to think the core of me was in politics, probably. It isn't. When you feel your mortality and your humanity you realize that, that the core of you is first of all being able to take care of your health."<ref name="nyt052000"/>  He said that he would instead devote the remainder of his mayoralty trying to overcome the hostile relations he had with many of the city's minority groups.<ref name="nyt052000"/>

==A change of Republicans==
[[Image:Ricklazio.jpg|thumb|146px|right|After Giuliani withdrew in May 2000, lesser-known Long Island Congressman [[Rick Lazio]] took his place.]]
While previous Republican nominee candidates and fellow Long Island Congressmen [[Rick Lazio]] and [[Peter T. King|Pete King]] had both indicated an interest in replacing Giuliani,<ref name="cnn052300">{{cite news | url=http://www.cnn.com/ALLPOLITICS/analysis/rothenberg/2000/05/23/rothenberg/index.html | title=New York Senate race far from settled | author=[[Stuart Rothenberg]] | publisher=[[CNN.com]] | date=2000-05-23 | accessdate=2007-11-02}}</ref> upon Giuliani's withdrawal the state party quickly rallied around Lazio,<ref name="nyt052000n"/> who had more campaign funds and who was viewed as a potentially strong candidate.<ref name="cnn052300"/>  In particular, Governor Pataki <U+2014> who never cared much for Giuliani to begin with<ref name="nyt052000n"/> <U+2014> was strongly in favor of Lazio, and praised him as "fresh, unencumbered challenger" to Clinton.<ref name="nyt052000n">{{cite news | url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9906E1DF103AF933A15756C0A9669C8B63 | title=Giuliani quits race for Senate, and G.O.P. rallies around Lazio | author=[[Adam Nagourney]] | publisher=[[The New York Times]] | date=2000-05-20 | accessdate=2007-12-18}}</ref>  This also caused a shuffle in New York's unique third-party ballot-line alignments: the [[Liberal Party of New York]], which was previously set to run Giuliani (whom they had supported in all three of his mayoral races), now switched to Clinton, while the [[Conservative Party of New York]], which had previously been loath to endorse the socially liberal Giuliani,<ref name="salon112707"/> lined up Lazio.<ref name="cnn052300"/>  Lazio accepted the unanimous approval of delegates to the Republican Party state convention at a hotel ballroom in [[Buffalo, New York|Buffalo]] on May 30.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2000/20000601/world.htm#6 | title=Lazio nominated to face Hillary | publisher=[[Associated Press]] for [[Chandigarh Tribune]] | date=2000-05-31 | accessdate=2008-01-17}}</ref>

Clinton now faced a lesser-known candidate in Lazio. While a relative moderate among House Republicans,<ref>{{cite news | url=http://archives.cnn.com/2000/ALLPOLITICS/stories/05/19/lazio.senate/ | title=Lazio boasts moderate record on some hot-button issues | author=Amy Paulson | publisher=[[CNN.com]] | date=2000-05-19 | accessdate=2007-12-17}}</ref> Lazio had frequently supported former House Speaker [[Newt Gingrich]], an unpopular figure among many New Yorkers.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2000/08/31/politics/main229691.shtml | title=Tying Rick To Newt | publisher=[[CBS News]] | date=2000-08-31 | accessdate=2007-12-17}}</ref> Lazio did bring to the table an ethnic suburban background familiar to many New Yorkers, and had a reputation as an energetic campaigner.<ref name="cnn052300"/><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.usatoday.com/news/opinion/e1915.htm | title=Lazio nominated to face Clinton | author=Martha T. Moore | publisher=[[USA Today]] | date=2000-05-30 | accessdate=2007-12-17}}</ref>

One formality left were New York's late-in-the-season primary elections on September 12, which in this case merely served to ratify the state party conventions' choices.  Lazio won unopposed,<ref name="cnn091300">{{cite news | url=http://archives.cnn.com/2000/ALLPOLITICS/stories/09/12/primary.day/index.html | title=Hillary Clinton wins New York Democratic primary | publisher=[[CNN.com]] | date=2000-09-13 | accessdate=2008-01-17}}</ref> while Clinton won 82&nbsp;percent of the vote<ref name="cnn091300b">{{cite news | url=http://archives.cnn.com/2000/ALLPOLITICS/stories/09/13/primary.day.01/index.html | title=Hillary Clinton, Lazio to debate tonight after winning New York primary races | publisher=[[CNN.com]] | date=2000-09-13 | accessdate=2008-01-17}}</ref> in easily defeating unknown Manhattan doctor Mark McMahon, who ran on the grounds that "the Clintons have tried to hijack the Democratic Party."<ref name="cnn091300b"/>  For her part, Clinton said that she was "surprised, in a way [to see her name in the voting booth]. I stood there for a minute, staring at my name."<ref name="cnn091300"/>  In any case, the general election was already well underway.

==General election==
The contest drew considerable national attention and both candidates were well-funded. By the end of the race, Democrat Clinton and Republicans Lazio and Giuliani had spent a combined $90 million,<ref name="nyt121300">{{cite news | url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9E04E1DB133FF930A25751C1A9669C8B63 | title= Lazio Sets Spending Mark for a Losing Senate Bid | author=Clifford J. Levy | publisher=''[[The New York Times]]'' | date=2000-12-13 | accessdate=2008-02-22}}</ref> the most of any U.S. Senate race in history.<ref name="nyt121300"/><ref>As of 2007, it still holds the record of most expensive Senate race.  See {{cite news | url=http://www.salon.com/news/feature/2007/11/27/rudy_hillary/ | title=When Rudy Met Hillary | author=Rob Polner | publisher=''[[Salon (magazine)|Salon]]'' | date=2007-11-27 | accessdate=2008-02-22}}</ref>  Lazio outspent Clinton $40 million to $29 million,<ref name="nyt121300"/> with Clinton also getting several million dollars in [[soft money]] from Democratic organizations.<ref name="nyt121300"/>  Among Clinton antagonists circles, direct mail-based fundraising groups such as the Emergency Committee to Stop Hillary Rodham Clinton sprung up,<ref>{{cite news | url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C0CE7DE1E31F934A15753C1A9669C8B63 | title= Clinton Rivals Raise Little Besides Rage | author=Clifford J. Levy | publisher=[[The New York Times]] | date=2000-10-27 | accessdate=2007-12-17}}</ref> sending out solicitations with apoplectic visions of: just as one Clinton leaves office, another gains office.

Clinton secured a broad base of support, including endorsements from conservation groups<ref>For example, the [[Sierra Club]] {{cite news | title= Hillary Clinton Is Endorsed By Sierra Club as Better Ally | author=Randal C. Archibold | url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C04E3DE1739F935A3575AC0A9669C8B63&n=Top%2fReference%2fTimes%20Topics%2fOrganizations%2fS%2fSierra%20Club | publisher=[[The New York Times]] | date=2000-09-06 | accessdate=2007-10-06}}</ref> and organized labor,<ref>{{cite news | title= Hillary Clinton Stars, Unrivaled, at Labor Day Parade | author=Steven Greenhouse | publisher=[[The New York Times]] | date=2000-09-10 | accessdate=2007-10-06}}</ref> but notably not the New York City police and firefighters' unions, which endorsed Lazio.<ref>{{cite news|title= Police Union Backs Lazio, Citing First Lady's Statement | url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9902E7DF1339F93BA3575AC0A9669C8B63&n=Top/Reference/Times%20Topics/People/C/Clinton,%20Hillary%20Rodham  | author=Elisabeth Bumiller | date=2000-09-08 | accessdate=2007-10-06}}</ref><ref name="firefighters">{{cite news | title = Clinton wins endorsement of city's firefighter unions | date=2006-04-19 | accessdate = 2007-10-06 | url = http://www.newsday.com/news/nationworld/nation/ny-nyhill0420,0,6369920.story | publisher = [[Associated Press]] }}</ref>  
While Clinton had a solid base of support in [[New York City]], candidates and observers expected the race to be decided in upstate New York where 45 percent of the state's voters live. During the campaign, Clinton vowed to improve the economic picture in upstate New York, promising that her plan would deliver 200,000 New York jobs over six years. Her plan included specific tax credits with the purpose of rewarding job creation and encouraging business investment, especially in the high-tech sector. She called for targeted personal tax cuts for college tuition and long-term care.<ref name="cnn110700">{{cite news | url=http://archives.cnn.com/2000/ALLPOLITICS/stories/11/07/senate.ny/ | title=Hillary Rodham Clinton scores historic win in New York | publisher=[[CNN.com]] | date=2000-11-08 | accessdate=2007-12-17}}</ref> 
Lazio faced a unique tactical problem campaigning upstate. The major issue there was the persistently weak local economy, which Lazio hoped to link to his opponent's husband's tenure in office. Attacks on the state of the upstate economy were frequently interpreted as criticism of incumbent Republican governor [[George Pataki]], however, limiting the effect of this line of attack. 

Opponents continued to make the carpetbagging issue a focal point throughout the race and during debates.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C0CE4D9103CF93AA35753C1A9669C8B63 | title=Excerpts From Second Debate Between Mrs. Clinton and Lazio | publisher=''[[The New York Times]]'' | date=2000-10-09 | accessdate=2008-02-18}}</ref>  [[Talk radio]] hammered on this, with New York-based [[Sean Hannity]] issuing a daily mantra, "Name me three things Hillary Clinton has ever done for the people of New York!"  Clinton's supporters pointed out that the state was receptive to national leaders, such as [[Robert F. Kennedy]] who was [[United States Senate election in New York, 1964|elected to the Senate in 1964]] despite similar accusations. In the end, according to exit polls conducted in the race, a majority of the voters dismissed the carpetbagging issue as unimportant.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://archives.cnn.com/2000/ALLPOLITICS/stories/11/08/senate.wrap/index.html | title=Ashcroft concedes as GOP clings to Senate lead | publisher=[[CNN.com]] | date=2000-11-08 | accessdate=2008-02-17}}</ref>

During the campaign, [[Independent Counsel]] [[Robert Ray (prosecutor)|Robert Ray]] filed his final reports regarding the long-running [[Whitewater (controversy)|Whitewater]],<ref name="cnn092000">[http://archives.cnn.com/2000/ALLPOLITICS/stories/09/20/whitewater/ "Ray: Insufficient evidence to prosecute Clintons in Whitewater probe"], [[CNN.com]], September 20, 2000. Retrieved April 30, 2007.</ref> "[[Travelgate]]",<ref name="cnn101800">[http://archives.cnn.com/2000/ALLPOLITICS/stories/10/18/travel.office "Ray: First lady's answers false in travel office probe, but no prosecution"], [[CNN.com]], October 18, 2000. Retrieved June 16, 2007.</ref> and "[[Filegate]]"<ref name="nyt031700">Neil A. Lewis, [http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9806EED8173AF934A25750C0A9669C8B63 "Report Clears White House In Inquiry Over F.B.I. Files"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', March 17, 2000. Retrieved June 9, 2007.</ref> investigations of the White House, each of which included specific investigations of Hillary Clinton actions.  The reports exonerated her on the files matter,<ref name="nyt031700"/> said there was insufficient evidence regarding her role in Whitewater,<ref name="cnn092000"/> and said that she had made factually false statements regarding the Travel Office firings but there was insufficient evidence to prosecute her.<ref name="cnn101800"/>  Although ''[[The New York Times]]'' editorialized that the release of the reports seemed possibly timed to coincide with the Senate election,<ref>{{cite news | url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9407EFDA1630F933A0575BC0A9669C8B63 | title= Mr. Ray's Ill-Timed Report | publisher=''[[The New York Times]]'' | date=2000-08-30 | accessdate=2008-02-16}}</ref> in practice the findings were not seen as likely to sway many voters' opinions.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2000/09/20/national/main234848.shtml | title=Whitewater: Case Closed | publisher=[[CBS News]] | date=2000-09-20 | accessdate=2008-02-16}}</ref>

A September 13, 2000 debate between Lazio and Clinton proved important.  Lazio was on the warpath against [[soft money]] and the amounts of it coming from the [[Democratic National Committee]] into Clinton's campaign, and challenged Clinton to agree to ban soft money from both campaigns.  He left his podium and waved his proposed paper agreement in Clinton's face;<ref name="gvn-212">Gerth, Van Natta Jr., ''Her Way'', pp. 212-213.</ref> many debate viewers thought he had invaded her [[personal space]]<ref name="salon112707"/> and as a result Clinton's support among women voters solidified.<ref name="gvn-212"/>

Late in the campaign Lazio criticised Clinton for accepting campaign donations from various Arab groups in the wake of the {{USS|Cole|DDG-67|6}} attack. This issue caused former New York Mayor [[Ed Koch]] to take out ads telling Lazio to "stop with the sleaze already,"<ref name="gvn-212"/> and did not change the dynamic of the race.

Clinton won the election on November 7 with 55% of the vote to Lazio's 43%,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.fec.gov/pubrec/fe2000/2000senate.htm#NY | title=Federal Elections 2000: U.S. Senate results | publisher=[[Federal Election Commission]] | accessdate=2007-12-17}}</ref> a difference larger than most observers had expected.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C06E7D71638F93AA35752C1A9669C8B63 | title=First Lady Emerges From Shadow And Begins to Cast Her Own | author=[[Elisabeth Bumiller]], Dean E. Murphy | publisher=''[[The New York Times]]'' | date=2000-11-09 | accessdate=2008-02-16}}</ref><ref name="nyt110900an"/> Clinton won the traditionally Democratic base of [[New York City]] by large margins, and carried suburban [[Westchester County, New York|Westchester County]], but lost heavily populated [[Long Island]], part of which Lazio represented in Congress. She won surprising victories in Upstate counties, such as [[Cayuga County, New York|Cayuga]], [[Rensselaer County, New York|Rensselaer]], and [[Niagara County, New York|Niagara]], to which her win has been attributed.

==Analysis of margin of victory==
In comparison with other results, this 12% margin was smaller than Gore's 25% margin over Bush in the [[United States presidential election in New York, 2000|state Presidential contest]], was slightly larger than the 10% margin by which fellow New York senator [[Charles Schumer]] defeated incumbent Republican [[Al D'Amato]] in the hotly contested 1998 race, but was considerably smaller than the 47% margin by which Senator Schumer won reelection in 2004 against little-known Republican challenger [[Howard Mills]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.cnn.com/ELECTION/1998/states/NY/S/index.html | title=Election Night 1998: New York | publisher=[[CNN.com]] | date=1998-11-04 | accessdate=2007-12-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.usatoday.com/news/politicselections/vote2004/ny.htm | title=Kerry, Schumer win in New York | publisher=[[Associated Press]] for [[USA Today]] | date=2004-11-03 | accessdate=2007-12-17}}</ref> The victory of a Democrat in the Senate election was not assured, because in recent decades the Republicans had won about half the elections for governor and senator.

Lazio's bid was handicapped by the weak performance of [[George W. Bush]] in New York in the 2000 election,<ref name="nyt110900an">{{cite news | url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9E0DE2DF1738F93AA35752C1A9669C8B63 | title=Mrs. Clinton Found Right Mix in Fame and Upstate Focus | author=[[Adam Nagourney]] | publisher=''[[The New York Times]]'' | date=2000-11-09 | accessdate=2008-02-18}}</ref> but it is also clear Hillary Clinton had made substantial inroads in upstate New York prior to Lazio's entry into the race.<ref name="nyt110900an"/> Exit polls also showed a large gender gap with Clinton running stronger than expected among moderate women and unaffiliated women.<ref name="nyt111200">{{cite news | url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F01E1DF1238F931A25752C1A9669C8B63 | title=It Took a Woman; How Gender Helped Elect Hillary Clinton | author=[[Elisabeth Bumiller]] | publisher=[[The New York Times]] | date=2000-11-12 | accessdate=2008-01-15}}</ref>

