==Post-election charges==
===Hasidic pardons===
In January 2001, two months after Hillary Clinton's election to the Senate, President Clinton [[List of people pardoned by Bill Clinton|pardoned]] four residents of the [[New Square, New York|New Square]] [[Hasidic Judaism|Hasidic]] enclave in [[Rockland County]], [[New York]], who had been convicted of defrauding the federal government of $30 million by establishing a fictitious religious school.<ref name="time041401">{{cite news | url=http://www.time.com/time/nation/article/0,8599,106316,00.html | title=U.S. Attorney White Keeps the Iron Hot | publisher=''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' | date=April 14, 2001 | accessdate=2007-05-24}}</ref><ref name="cnn-tarnish">{{cite news | author=Carol Clark | url=http://www.cnn.com/SPECIALS/2001/pardons/overview.html | title=Pardons may tarnish Clinton legacy | publisher=[[CNN.com]] | date=2001 | accessdate=2007-05-24}}</ref>
New Square had voted almost unanimously for Hillary Clinton in the New York Senate race. A lawyer following the matter stated that even if Hillary Clinton had promised to lobby her husband for clemency in exchange for the town's votes <U+2014> a claim for which there was no proof <U+2014> it would be difficult to establish a crime had taken place: "Politicians make promises all the time. That's nothing new <U+2014> or illegal."<ref name="time041401"/> Hillary Clinton acknowledged sitting in on a post-election meeting discussing possible clemency for the four, but said she had played no part in her husband's decision.<ref name="cnn-tarnish"/> 

A federal investigation launched to investigate various Clinton pardons,<ref name="time041401"/> closed its investigation of the New Square matter in June 2002 by taking no action against Bill Clinton, Hillary Clinton, or any residents of New Square.<ref name="cnn062002">{{cite news | url=http://archives.cnn.com/2002/ALLPOLITICS/06/20/clinton.clemency/index.html | title=Clinton cleared in one probe of clemency grants | publisher=[[CNN.com]] | date=June 20, 2002 | accessdate=2007-05-24}}</ref>

===Hollywood fundraiser===
[[Image:Hillary Clinton and her largest donor Peter Paul.jpg|thumb|146px|right|Hillary Clinton with her largest 2000 contributor, Peter Paul, at the [[Gala Hollywood Farewell Salute to President Clinton]].]]  Hillary Clinton's former finance director, [[David Rosen (politics)|David Rosen]], was indicted on January 7, 2005 on campaign finance charges related to a fund-raising event produced by [[Peter F. Paul]].  Paul, a convicted drug dealer who would soon after be convicted on stock fraud charges after being extradited from [[Brazil]], stated that he spent $1.2 million to produce the August 12, 2000 [[Hollywood Gala Salute to President William Jefferson Clinton]] event, which was both a tribute to honor President Clinton and a fundraiser for the First Lady's 2000 Senate campaign. The [[United States Department of Justice|Justice Department]] indictment charged Rosen with filing false reports with the [[Federal Election Commission]] by reporting only $400,000 in contributions. On May 27, 2005, the jury acquitted Rosen on all counts.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20050527/ap_on_re_us/clinton_fundraising_probe | title=~ Clinton Fundraising Probe | publisher=[[Associated Press]] for [[Yahoo! News]] | date=2005-05-27}}</ref>  On January 5, 2006 it was reported that Clinton's campaign group agreed to pay a $35,000 fine related to the underreporting of the fundraiser's expenses.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.cnn.com/2006/POLITICS/01/05/hillaryclinton.fundra.ap/index.html | title=~ Hillary Clinton Fundraising | publisher=[[CNN.com]] | date=2006-01-05}}</ref>

Peter Paul has also filed a civil suit in this matter, ''[[Paul v. Clinton]]''.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.hillcap.org | title=Peter Paul blah blah | publisher=Hillcap.org | accessdate=2006}}</ref>  On April 10, 2006, the judge in charge of the case removed Hillary Clinton as a defendant, citing a lack of evidence. However, she may still be called to testify as a witness in the case.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.nysun.com/article/30698?access=709915 | title=Judge Drops Senator Clinton From Lawsuit | author=Josh Gerstein | publisher=[[The New York Sun]] | date=2006-04-10 | accessdate=2007-12-17}}</ref>  The removal was upheld by the [[California Courts of Appeal#Second District|California Second District Court of Appeal]] on October 16, 2007.<ref name="ap101607">{{cite news | url=http://www.wtop.com/?nid=213&sid=1270070 | title=Court Says Clinton Should Not Be in Suit | author=Greg Risling | publisher=[[Associated Press]] for [[WTOP-FM|WTOP]] | date=2007-10-16 | accessdate=2007-11-01}}</ref>

Meanwhile, by the time of [[Hillary Rodham Clinton presidential campaign, 2008|Hillary Clinton's 2008 presidential campaign]], a 13-minute video produced by Paul and describing his various allegations against Hillary Clinton had become quite popular on the Internet, gaining 1.4 million hits on [[Google Video]] and about 350,000 on [[YouTube]] in a single week in October 2007.<ref name="ap102907">{{cite news | url=http://ap.google.com/article/ALeqM5gUtFgO8foY5-Gy8CFMqcRyGxtxJQD8SJ7AV00 | title=Anti-Clinton Video Draws Attention | author=Jim Kuhnhenn | publisher=[[Associated Press]] | date=2007-10-29 | accessdate=2007-11-01}}</ref>

==Legacy==
Clinton's victory would establish her as an effective campaigner and an electoral force on her own, able to capture Republican and independent votes and overcome her polarizing image.<ref name="nyt110900an"/>  She would [[United States Senate election in New York, 2006|easily win re-election in 2006]], and in 2007 began [[Hillary Rodham Clinton presidential campaign, 2008|her presidential campaign for 2008]].

Lazio gave up his House seat to run for Senate.  Following his defeat, which set a record for the most money spent in a losing Senate effort,<ref name="nyt121300"/> he took positions in the corporate world and avoided electoral politics until becoming a candidate for in [[New York gubernatorial election, 2010|New York's 2010 gubernatorial election]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://capitalnews9.com/region12content/top_stories/482987/lazio-expected-to-announce-candidacy-for-governor/ | title=Lazio announces candidacy for governor | author= | publisher=[[Capital News 9]] | date=2009-09-21 | accessdate=2010-02-21}}</ref>

Giuliani would undergo treatment for his cancer and eventually recover; he would also divorce Donna Hanover and eventually marry Judith Nathan.  After his campaign withdrawal, his political future looked uncertain at best.<ref name="salon112707"/>  But less than a year after the senate general election, the [[September 11, 2001 terrorist attacks]] took place, with Giuliani still mayor.  Giuliani's performance in the aftermath of September 11 earned him many accolades and resurrected his political prospects.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.boston.com/news/nation/articles/2007/11/08/skills_at_ready_when_crisis_struck/?page=full | author=Brian C. Mooney | title=Skills at ready when crisis struck | publisher=''[[The Boston Globe]]'' | date=2007-11-08 | accessdate=2008-02-18}}</ref>  After a successful stint in the private sector, in 2007 he also began [[Rudy Giuliani presidential campaign, 2008|his presidential campaign for 2008]].

Throughout much of 2007, Clinton and Giuliani led in national polls for their parties' respective nominations, and media reports often looked back to the 2000 "race that wasn't" as a preview of what might lie in wait for the entire nation in 2008.<ref name="salon112707"/><ref name="nyt112807"/>  Such extrapolating ended with the Giuliani campaign's precipitous decline and January 2008 withdrawal. Clinton as well failed to gain the 2008 nomination and, in June 2008, she finished in a close second place to Illinois Senator [[Barack Obama]].

In December 2008, Lowey would have another chance at the Senate seat, when Clinton was nominated for [[U.S. Secretary of State]] by President-elect Obama and Lowey was considered a front-runner to be named as her appointed replacement.<ref name="pol120108">{{cite news | url=http://www.politico.com/blogs/thecrypt/1208/Lowey_doesnt_want_Clintons_Senate_seat.html | title=Lowey withdraws from race to replace Clinton | author=Thrush, Glenn | publisher=''[[The Politico]]'' | date=2008-12-01 | accessdate=2008-12-05}}</ref>  But Lowey withdrew from consideration, as in the intervening years she had gained enough seniority to become one of the powerful "cardinals" on the [[United States House Committee on Appropriations|House Appropriations Committee]] and did not want to relinquish that position.<ref name="pol120108"/>  When [[Caroline Kennedy]] announced her interest in the vacancy, comparisons were drawn to Clinton in 2000, with both being famous people seeking to hold elective office for the first time.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2008/dec/18/caroline-kennedy-senate-profile | title=Caroline Kennedy: Born survivor makes Senate bid | author=Goldenberg, Suzanne | publisher=''[[The Guardian]]'' | date=2008-12-18 | accessdate=2009-03-21}}</ref>  Others pointed out that Clinton had won election to the office while Kennedy would first be appointed.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.salon.com/politics/war_room/2008/12/16/kennedy_clinton/ | title=Why Caroline Kennedy is not Hillary Clinton | author=Koppelman, Alex | publisher=''[[Salon (magazine)|Salon]]'' | date=2008-12-16 | accessdate=2009-03-21}}</ref>  In any case, Kennedy's effort soon faltered, in part due to not having the same desire or willingness to work for the seat as Clinton had had,<ref>{{cite news | url=http://cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com/2008/12/31/choice-of-kennedy-for-senate-no-longer-seems-inevitable | title=Choice of Kennedy for Senate No Longer Seems Inevitable | author=Lee, Jennifer 8. | publisher=''[[The New York Times]]'' | date=2008-12-31 | accessdate=2009-03-21}}</ref> and she soon withdrew as abruptly as she had entered.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com/2008/12/31/choice-of-kennedy-for-senate-no-longer-seems-inevitable | title=Caroline Kennedy officially withdraws from race for Secretary of State Hillary Clinton's Senate seat | author=Lovett, Kenneth | publisher=''[[New York Daily News]]'' | date=2009-01-22 | accessdate=2009-03-21}}</ref>  

[[Kirsten Gillibrand]] received the appointment, and attention then turned to who would run against her in the [[United States Senate special election in New York, 2010|2010 Senate special election]].  By November 2009, Giuliani was seriously considering a run for his old would-have-been Senate seat,<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/politics/2009/11/19/2009-11-19_former_mayor_rudy_giuliani_to_announce_plan_to_run_for_us_senate.html | title=Rudy Giuliani will very likely seek U.S. Senate seat, and if elected maybe 2012 White House: source | author=Kenneth Lovett | author2=Elizabeth Benjamin | author3=David Saltonstall | newspaper=[[New York Daily News]] | date=2009-11-19 | accessdate=2010-02-21}}</ref> but the following month he announced he was not running for it or anything else in 2010, possibly signalling an end to his political career.<ref name="nyt122209">{{cite news | url=http://www.nytimes.com/2009/12/23/nyregion/23rudy.html | title=Giuliani Says Farewell, for Now, to Politics | author=Michael Powell | newspaper=[[The New York Times]] | date=2009-12-22 | accessdate=2010-02-21 }}</ref><ref name="pol122309">{{cite news | url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/1209/30920.html | title=Rudy Giuliani exits national stage | author=Jonathan Martin | author2=Ben Smith | newspaper=[[The Politico]] | date=2009-12-23 | accessdate=2010-02-21 }}</ref>

